.TH XRANDR-PROFILE 1 "May 2026" "xrandr-profile VERSION" "General Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
xrandr-profile \- save and restore XRandR display profiles
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B xrandr-profile
.RB [ \-\-save
.IR profile ]
.RB [ \-\-load
.IR profile ]
.RB [ \-\-delete
.IR profile ]
.RB [ \-\-list ]
.RB [ \-\-list-all ]
.RB [ \-\-list-current ]
.RB [ \-\-name ]
.RB [ \-\-version ]
.RB [ \-\-help ]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B xrandr-profile
is a lightweight XRandR profile manager.

It saves and restores display configurations based on connected monitor
hardware using EDID matching, allowing layouts to be restored even when
monitors appear under different output names.

Profiles store monitor configuration properties including position,
resolution, refresh rate, rotation, reflection, panning, and scaling
transform.

.PP
When run without arguments,
.B xrandr-profile
automatically applies the most recently used profile matching the current
monitor configuration, if available.

.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.BI \-\-save " profile"
Save the current display configuration as
.IR profile .

.TP
.BI \-\-load " profile"
Load the specified
.IR profile .

.TP
.BI \-\-delete " profile"
Delete the specified
.IR profile .

.TP
.B \-\-list
List saved profiles matching the current monitor configuration.

.TP
.B \-\-list-all
List all saved profiles.

.TP
.B \-\-list-current
Print the current active display configuration.

.TP
.B \-\-name
Print only the name of the profiles.

.TP
.B \-\-version
Print version information and exit.

.TP
.B \-\-help
Display usage information and exit.

.SH FILES

.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/xrandr-profile/profiles
Default profile storage directory.

.TP
.I ~/.config/xrandr-profile/profiles
Fallback profile storage directory when
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is unset.

.SH EXAMPLES

.TP
Save the current layout:
.B xrandr-profile --save work

.TP
Restore a saved layout:
.B xrandr-profile --load docked

.TP
Automatically restore the last matching profile:
.B xrandr-profile

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR xrandr (1),
.BR X (7),
.BR autorandr (1)

